WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.840
Let me start with a little story, because I think it'll help explain the technicalities

00:03.840 --> 00:07.080
of what's actually happening behind the scenes.

00:07.080 --> 00:11.560
So imagine a website where you can post images and comments underneath.

00:11.560 --> 00:13.520
So think of, say, Facebook.

00:13.520 --> 00:15.880
But I'm not suggesting Facebook is vulnerable to this, okay?

00:15.880 --> 00:17.400
You need to find a vulnerable website.

00:17.400 --> 00:20.440
But let's just all think about Facebook, because there's probably a website we're all

00:20.440 --> 00:22.000
familiar with.

00:22.000 --> 00:26.120
So I log into Facebook one day, and I noticed that my buddy has posted a picture of him

00:26.120 --> 00:27.440
and his daughter.

00:27.440 --> 00:31.080
And being the very good friend that I am, I decide to post a comment underneath.

00:31.080 --> 00:33.520
And so I write something like, oh, what a lovely picture.

00:33.520 --> 00:35.400
It's too bad she looks just like you do.

00:35.400 --> 00:37.720
So that's the crappy comment I leave.

00:37.720 --> 00:40.640
Now what happens when I hit submit?

00:40.640 --> 00:43.440
That comment gets sent to Facebook servers.

00:43.440 --> 00:46.360
The comment is stored in a database somewhere.

00:46.360 --> 00:52.000
And now every subsequent user that goes and views that picture is going to see my crappy

00:52.000 --> 00:54.120
comment underneath.

00:54.120 --> 00:57.920
And so what's happening is my comment data is actually being stored on the server.

00:57.920 --> 01:02.720
And then every subsequent user that visits the website, that HTML code contains the

01:02.720 --> 01:03.720
comment.

01:03.720 --> 01:07.960
And the user's browser is downloading that comment, and it's displaying it, like it's

01:07.960 --> 01:09.440
supposed to.

01:09.440 --> 01:10.760
So that's the scenario, okay?

01:10.760 --> 01:13.680
Now, here's what's going to happen.

01:13.680 --> 01:17.120
Our baddie here, you can tell they're baddie, right, the fedora.

01:17.120 --> 01:21.760
Our baddie here is going to discover a vulnerable website, and it has to be a vulnerable website,

01:21.760 --> 01:24.160
which I'll explain why in a few minutes.

01:24.160 --> 01:27.080
So our baddie discovers a vulnerable website.

01:27.080 --> 01:28.360
And here's what our baddie does.

01:28.360 --> 01:32.200
Our baddie injects some malicious code into the web page.

01:32.200 --> 01:34.280
And that sounds very technical, doesn't it?

01:34.280 --> 01:40.920
But it could literally be as simple as typing some code in a comment field and hitting submit.

01:40.920 --> 01:45.080
And what's the code that you're going to type into the comment field of the website?

01:45.080 --> 01:46.720
JavaScript.

01:46.720 --> 01:49.440
Now why does it have to be a vulnerable website?

01:49.440 --> 01:54.440
Well, because no website should ever just accept JavaScript code as a comment and store

01:54.440 --> 02:00.400
that code in the database, and especially then redisplay all that code to every user.

02:00.400 --> 02:04.160
But that's why our baddie discovers a vulnerable website.

02:04.160 --> 02:08.560
So our baddie injects the code into the web page into the website, they submit their comment,

02:08.560 --> 02:11.360
the comment gets stored on the server.

02:11.360 --> 02:12.960
Now what happens?

02:12.960 --> 02:17.520
Every subsequent user that visits that website, their browser is going to download the web

02:17.520 --> 02:22.880
page, and embedded in that web page is going to be the JavaScript code.

02:22.880 --> 02:25.960
And their browser is going to do exactly what it's designed to do.

02:25.960 --> 02:30.960
Their browser is going to parse the HTML page, it's going to come across the JavaScript,

02:30.960 --> 02:36.160
and it's going to execute the JavaScript, it's what it's designed to do.

02:36.160 --> 02:41.520
And now when our victim's browser executes that JavaScript code, what typically happens?

02:41.520 --> 02:45.920
Well, some data is sent back to our baddie here.

02:45.920 --> 02:49.360
So this is an example of stored cross-site scripting.

02:49.360 --> 02:50.720
Why do we call it stored?

02:50.720 --> 02:55.520
Well, it's because the JavaScript code is stored on the server.

02:55.520 --> 03:00.400
We also call it persistent, and the reason we call it persistent is because every subsequent

03:00.400 --> 03:05.120
user that goes to this particular page and views, you know, and downloads this malicious

03:05.120 --> 03:08.080
code, it's going to execute on their browser.

03:08.080 --> 03:12.400
So stored, persistent, cross-site scripting.

03:12.400 --> 03:15.320
Now let's talk about another type of cross-site scripting.

03:15.320 --> 03:18.360
This is known as reflected cross-site scripting.

03:18.360 --> 03:23.360
So I'm going to set up another little scenario to help you imagine how this works.

03:23.360 --> 03:26.400
Imagine going to a website like Google.com.

03:26.400 --> 03:31.320
When you go to Google, when you go to Google.com, and you type in a search query in the search

03:31.320 --> 03:34.400
bar and hit search, what happens?

03:34.400 --> 03:40.040
Well, the search results page says, here are your search results for cat or dog or whatever

03:40.040 --> 03:43.000
you've searched for.

03:43.000 --> 03:45.680
So imagine that scenario, OK?

03:45.680 --> 03:46.760
So here's what's going to happen.

03:46.760 --> 03:50.360
Our baddie is going to do, again, discover a vulnerable website.

03:50.360 --> 03:54.040
And our baddie is going to first create a URL.

03:54.040 --> 03:56.640
A URL stands for a universal resource locator.

03:56.640 --> 04:00.680
This is what you type up in your browser bar to go to a particular site or page on a

04:00.680 --> 04:02.160
website.

04:02.160 --> 04:05.880
And what our baddie is going to do here is think of Google.com again.

04:05.880 --> 04:10.720
When you type in Google.com and you search for something, the search results URL page will

04:10.720 --> 04:17.600
say Google.com, question mark, search equals, whatever you searched for.

04:17.600 --> 04:21.720
Our baddie is going to create a URL for like that, except in the search field, instead of

04:21.720 --> 04:27.120
putting in some word or some sentence, what's our baddie going to put in the URL?

04:27.120 --> 04:28.760
JavaScript code.

04:28.760 --> 04:33.240
So our baddie creates this URL containing the JavaScript code.

04:33.240 --> 04:36.360
Sends it to our victim here.

04:36.360 --> 04:40.920
And through some sort of social engineering technique, maybe phishing or something like

04:40.920 --> 04:46.280
that, our baddie here somehow convinces the user to click on the URL.

04:46.280 --> 04:50.920
When the user clicks on the URL, that sends the request to the web server.

04:50.920 --> 04:54.560
The web server is going to then reflect that code back to the user.

04:54.560 --> 04:55.560
It's like the search.

04:55.560 --> 04:59.680
It's like the page is saying, here are your search results for JavaScript code.

04:59.680 --> 05:04.640
So the website is going to reflect the malicious code back to the user.

05:04.640 --> 05:09.800
The malicious code is going to be contained in the page that comes back to the user.

05:09.800 --> 05:13.080
And once our users browse are going to do, exactly what it's designed to do.

05:13.080 --> 05:19.160
It's going to parse through the page, hit the malicious JavaScript code and execute it.

05:19.160 --> 05:26.400
And once the final step here, well, this malicious code is going to run and it's going to send

05:26.400 --> 05:29.240
some data back to the baddie once again.

05:29.240 --> 05:34.400
So overall, it's the same effect, which is the target of attack here is the user.

05:34.400 --> 05:39.240
And in both stored and reflected and, sorry, in both stored and persistent and reflected

05:39.240 --> 05:43.400
cross-site scripting, it's all about sending data back to the baddie.

05:43.400 --> 05:48.360
But in reflected cross-site scripting, there's a few important things to understand here.

05:48.360 --> 05:52.600
Number one, why do we call it reflected cross-site scripting?

